1. Reflection of Light

When light bounces off a surface. Let's explore the fundamental law that governs it.

The Law of Reflection

What is the golden rule of reflection?

The angle of incidence is EQUAL to the angle of reflection.

i = r

Used in mirrors, cameras, and optical fibres.

Specular vs. Diffuse Reflection

Does all reflection create a clear image?

Specular Reflection

Occurs on smooth surfaces (like a mirror). Parallel incident rays are reflected as parallel rays, forming a clear image.

Diffuse Reflection

Occurs on rough surfaces (like paper). Parallel incident rays are scattered in all directions. No clear image is formed.

Investigating Reflection

How can we prove the law?

Experiment Setup:

  • Use a ray box, slit, paper, and a plane mirror.
  • Draw the mirror's position and the normal line.
  • Shine a light ray at the mirror.
  • Mark the incident and reflected rays with crosses.
  • Measure angles 'i' and 'r' with a protractor.
  • Repeat for different angles to confirm i = r.

(Refer to the diagram showing the experimental setup for reflection)

2. Refraction of Light

Light doesn't always bounce, sometimes it bends! This happens when light passes from one medium to another.

The Core Concept: Bending Light

Refraction is the change in direction of light as it passes across a boundary between two media. This happens because the speed and wavelength of light change. The frequency remains constant.

Less Dense ‚Üí More Dense (e.g. Air to Glass)

Bends TOWARDS the normal

i > r

More Dense ‚Üí Less Dense (e.g. Glass to Air)

Bends AWAY from the normal

i < r

(Refer to the diagram showing refraction through a glass block)

3. Refractive Index (n)

A number that tells us how much light slows down in a substance. No units!

Calculating 'n' with Angles

Using Snell's Law

n =
sin(i) sin(r)

Use this when light enters a substance from air/vacuum.

Calculating 'n' with Speed

The fundamental definition!

n =
Speed of light in vacuum (c) Speed of light in substance (v)

Since v is always less than c, n is always > 1.

Investigating Refraction

How to find 'n' for a glass block.

Experiment:

  1. Place a glass block on paper and draw around it.
  2. Shine a ray of light through the block.
  3. Mark the incident and emergent rays.
  4. Remove the block, draw the refracted ray inside.
  5. Draw the normal at the point of incidence.
  6. Measure angles 'i' and 'r'.
  7. Calculate n using Snell's Law. Repeat for accuracy.

4. Total Internal Reflection (TIR)

What happens when light is trapped inside a denser medium? It reflects perfectly!

The Two Golden Rules for TIR

‚ñæ
  1. The light must travel from a more dense to a less dense medium.
  2. The angle of incidence (i) must be GREATER than the critical angle (c).

What is the Critical Angle (c)?

‚ñæ

It's the specific angle of incidence where the angle of refraction becomes exactly 90 degrees.

(Refer to the diagram showing i < c, i = c, and i > c)

sin(c) =
1n

Uses of TIR

‚ñæ
  • Optical Fibres: A very thin glass core is surrounded by cladding with a lower refractive index. This ensures TIR happens at the core-cladding boundary, trapping light inside. Used in telecommunications and medicine (endoscopes).
  • Periscopes: Use right-angled prisms to reflect light 90 degrees. This is more efficient than mirrors.

5. Lenses & Ray Diagrams

Lenses use refraction to form images by focusing or spreading out light.

Key Lens Terminology

Tap to reveal definitions

  • Principal Axis: Line passing straight through the centre of the lens.
  • Optical Centre (C): The exact centre of the lens.
  • Principal Focus (F): The point where rays parallel to the principal axis converge (or appear to diverge from).
  • Focal Length (f): The distance from the optical centre (C) to the principal focus (F).

Converging (Convex) Lens

Fatter in the middle. It causes parallel rays of light to converge at the principal focus (F).

Ray Diagram Rules:

  1. Ray parallel to axis ‚Üí Refracts through F.
  2. Ray through optical centre C ‚Üí No deviation.
  3. Ray through F ‚Üí Refracts parallel to axis.

Diverging (Concave) Lens

Thinner in the middle. It causes parallel rays to diverge as if from a virtual principal focus (F).

Ray Diagram Rules:

  1. Ray parallel to axis ‚Üí Refracts as if from F.
  2. Ray through optical centre C ‚Üí No deviation.
  3. Ray aimed at F (far side) ‚Üí Refracts parallel to axis.

(Refer to diagrams showing lens shapes and ray rules)

6. Real vs Virtual Images

Lenses can form two types of images. Let's see the difference.

Real Images

Tap to learn more

  • Formed where light rays physically intersect.
  • Can be projected onto a screen.
  • Always inverted (upside down).
  • Formed by converging lenses when object is placed outside the focal length (distance > f).

Virtual Images

Tap to learn more

  • Formed where light rays appear to diverge from.
  • Cannot be projected onto a screen.
  • Always upright (the right way up).
  • Formed by all diverging lenses, plane mirrors, and converging lenses when the object is inside the focal length (distance < f).

Special Case: The Magnifying Glass

When you place an object inside the focal length of a converging lens, it produces a magnified, virtual, and upright image. This is how a magnifying glass works!

(Refer to the ray diagram for a magnifying glass)

7. Correcting Sight

How lenses help us see clearly.

Short-sightedness (Myopia)

Can see near objects, distant objects are blurry.

Problem: The eye lens is too powerful or the eyeball is too long. Light from distant objects focuses in front of the retina.

Solution: Use a diverging (concave) lens to spread the light out before it enters the eye, moving the focus point back onto the retina.

Long-sightedness (Hyperopia)

Can see distant objects, near objects are blurry.

Problem: The eye lens is too weak or the eyeball is too short. Light from near objects focuses behind the retina.

Solution: Use a converging (convex) lens to focus the light more strongly, moving the focus point forward onto the retina.

8. Dispersion of Light

Ever seen a rainbow from a prism? That's dispersion! It's the splitting of white light into its different colours.

Why does it happen?

Each colour travels at a different speed in a medium like glass, causing them to refract by different amounts.

Red Light: Longest wavelength ‚Üí Refracts the least.

Violet Light: Shortest wavelength ‚Üí Refracts the most.

(Refer to the diagram showing dispersion through a prism)

The Visible Spectrum

Tap to see the order!

Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Blue, Indigo, Violet

Monochromatic Light (Extended)

This is light of a single frequency (and therefore a single colour). A laser is a perfect example of a monochromatic light source. Since it's only one colour, it will refract but it cannot be dispersed.
